            <pb n="4" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Rock Music in South America.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;The gra-<lb break="no"/>nitic rock on which we rested is one of those
                    where tra-<lb break="no"/>vellers on the shores of the Orinoco have heard,
                        from<lb break="yes"/>time to time, towards sunrise, subterraneous sounds,<lb
                        break="yes"/>resembling the tones of the organ. The Missionaries<lb
                        break="yes"/>call these stones musical slabs (<hi rendition="#i">laxas de
                        musica</hi>). &#x201C;It<lb break="yes"/>is witchcraft (<hi rendition="#i"
                        >cosa de bruxas</hi>),&#x201D; said our young Indian<lb break="yes"/>pilot,
                    who could speak English. We never ourselves<lb break="yes"/>heard these
                    mysterious sounds, either at Carichana-<lb break="maybe"/>Vieja, or in the Upper
                    Orinoco; but, from information<lb break="yes"/>given us by witnesses worthy of
                    belief, the existerce<lb break="yes"/>of the phenomenon, which seems to depend
                    on a certain<lb break="yes"/>state of the atmosphere, cannot be denied. The
                        shelves<lb break="yes"/>of rock are full of very narrow and deep crevices.
                        They<lb break="yes"/>are heated during the day to 48° or 50°. I several<lb
                        break="yes"/>times found their temperature at the surface, during<lb
                        break="yes"/>the night, at 39°, the surrounding atmosphere being<lb
                        break="yes"/>at 28°. It may easily be conceived that the difference<lb
                        break="yes"/>of temperature between the subterranean and the ex-<lb
                        break="no"/>ternal air attains its maximum about sun-rise, or at that<lb
                        break="yes"/>moment which is at the same time farthest from the<lb
                        break="yes"/>period of the maximum of the heat of the preceding<lb
                        break="yes"/>day. May not these organ-like sounds, which are heard<lb
                        break="yes"/>when a person lays his ear in contact with the stone, be<lb
                        break="yes"/>the effect of a current of air that issues out through<lb
                        break="yes"/>the crevices? Does not the impulse of the air against<lb
                        break="yes"/>the elastic spangles of mica, which intercept the crevices,<lb
                        break="yes"/>contribute to modify the sounds? May we not believe<lb
                        break="yes"/>that the ancient inhabitants of Egypt, in passing in-<lb
                        break="no"/>cessantly up and down the Nile, had made the same<lb break="yes"
                    />observation on some rock of the Thebaid; and that the<lb break="yes"
                    />&#x201C;music of the rocks&#x201D; there, led to the jugglery of the<lb
                        break="yes"/>priests in the statue of Memnon? Perhaps, when &#x201C;the<lb
                        break="yes"/>rosy-fingered Aurora rendered her son, the glorious<lb
                        break="yes"/>Memnon, vocal,&#x2019; the voice was that of a man hidden<lb
                        break="yes"/>beneath the pedestal of the statue; but the observation<lb
                        break="yes"/>of the natives of the Orinoco, which we relate, seems<lb
                        break="yes"/>to explain, in a natural manner, what gave rise to the<lb
                        break="yes"/>Egyptian belief of a stone that poured forth sounds at<lb
                        break="yes"/>sunrise. Almost at the same period at which I com-<lb
                        break="no"/>municated these conjectures to some of the learned men<lb
                        break="yes"/>of Europe, three French travellers, MM. Jomard, Jol-<lb
                        break="no"/>lois, and Devilliers, were led to analogous ideas. They<lb
                        break="yes"/>heard at sunrise, in a monument of granite, at the centre<lb
                        break="yes"/>of the spot on which stands the palace of Karnak, a<lb
                        break="yes"/>noise resembling that of a string breaking. Now this<lb
                        break="yes"/>comparison is precisely that which the ancients employed<lb
                        break="yes"/>in speaking of the voice of Memnon. The French<lb break="yes"
                    />travellers thought, like me, that the passage of rarefied<lb break="yes"/>air
                    through the fissures of a sonorous stone might have<lb break="yes"/>suggested to
                    the Egyptian priests the invention of the<lb break="yes"/>juggleries of the
                    Memnonium. &#x2014; <hi rendition="#i">From Humboldt&#x2019;s<lb break="yes"
                        />&#x201C;Personal Narrative,&#x201D; Translated and Edited by<lb
                            break="yes"/>Thomasina Ross.</hi>
                </p>
